{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Millions of workers have been disconnected from the work force. If they are not reconnected, the costs to them and to society will be grim.", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by Dean Baker, co-director of the Center for Economic and Policy Research, and Kevin Hassett, director of economic policy studies at the American Enterprise Institute, suggests that America follow Germany's lead in dealing with the dire problems of long-term unemployment; cites Germany's success with job-sharing, in which employees are retained with small government subsidies, leading to a work force that is emotionally healthier and fewer chronically unemployed workers.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "9", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Dean", "role": "reported", "lastname": "BAKER", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "Kevin", "role": "reported", "lastname": "HASSETT", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By DEAN BAKER and KEVIN HASSETT", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/13/opinion/sunday/the-human-disaster-of-unemployment.html", "lead_paragraph": "Millions of workers have been disconnected from the work force. If they are not reconnected, the costs to them and to society will be grim.", "headline": {"seo": "The Human Disaster of Unemployment", "main": "The Human Disaster of Unemployment", "print_headline": "The Human Disaster of Unemployment", "content_kicker": "Opinion", "kicker": "Opinion"}, "_id": "53f6ab7e38f0d821a37b24f1", "word_count": "1133", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2012/05/13/sunday-review/13UNEMPLOYMENT/13UNEMPLOYMENT-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2012/05/13/sunday-review/13UNEMPLOYMENT/13UNEMPLOYMENT-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 424, "url": "images/2012/05/13/sunday-review/13UNEMPLOYMENT/13UNEMPLOYMENT-articleLarge-v2.jpg", "legacy"